      "summary": "Two more ways to group values.",
      "xpReward": 50,
      "steps": [
        {
          "kind": "explainer",
          "payload": {
            "title": "Immutable and unique",
            "body": "A tuple uses ( ) and can't be changed after you make it — great for fixed data like coordinates. A set uses { } and keeps only unique values.",
            "codeSample": "point = (3, 4)      # tuple\ntags = {\"fun\", \"easy\", \"fun\"}  # set → {\"fun\", \"easy\"}"
          }
        },
        {
          "kind": "mcq",
          "payload": {
            "prompt": "What makes a set special?",
            "options": ["It stores keys", "It removes duplicates", "It's always sorted"],
            "correctIndex": 1,
            "explanation": "A set automatically drops duplicate values."
          }
        },
        {
          "kind": "codeFill",
          "payload": {
            "prompt": "Create a tuple with the colors red and blue.",
            "codeBefore": "colors = ",
            "codeAfter": "",
            "choices": ["(\"red\", \"blue\")", "[\"red\", \"blue\"]", "{\"red\", \"blue\"}"],
            "correctIndex": 0,
            "explanation": "Parentheses make a tuple; square brackets make a list."
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "python-a1",
      "languageID": "python",
      "tier": "advanced",
      "order": 11,
      "title": "Classes and objects",
      "summary": "Design your own types.",
      "xpReward": 60,
      "steps": [
        {
          "kind": "explainer",
          "payload": {
            "title": "class, __init__, and self",
            "body": "A class is a blueprint. __init__ runs when you create a new object. self is the object itself — use self.name to store data on it.",
            "codeSample": "class Dog:\n    def __init__(self, name):\n        self.name = name\n    def bark(self):\n        print(f\"{self.name} says woof!\")\nDog(\"Rex\").bark()"
          }
        },
        {
          "kind": "mcq",
          "payload": {
            "prompt": "What is self in a Python class?",
            "options": ["The class name", "The current object", "The computer"],
            "correctIndex": 1,
            "explanation": "self refers to the specific object you're working with right now."
          }
        },
        {
          "kind": "codeFill",
          "payload": {
            "prompt": "Finish the class declaration.",
            "codeBefore": "",
            "codeAfter": " Cat:\n    pass",
            "choices": ["class", "def", "struct"],
            "correctIndex": 0,
            "explanation": "class starts a class definition in Python."
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "python-a2",
      "languageID": "python",
      "tier": "advanced",
      "order": 12,
      "title": "List comprehensions",
      "summary": "Build lists in one clean line.",
      "xpReward": 65,
      "steps": [
        {
          "kind": "explainer",
          "payload": {
            "title": "Shorthand for loops",
            "body": "A list comprehension builds a new list from an old one in a single line. Pattern: [expression for item in list if condition].",
            "codeSample": "nums = [1, 2, 3, 4]\nevens = [n for n in nums if n % 2 == 0]\nprint(evens) # [2, 4]"
          }
        },
        {
          "kind": "mcq",
          "payload": {
            "prompt": "What does [x*2 for x in [1,2,3]] produce?",
            "options": ["[1, 2, 3]", "[2, 4, 6]", "[1, 4, 9]"],
            "correctIndex": 1,
            "explanation": "Each value is doubled: 1*2, 2*2, 3*2 = 2, 4, 6."
          }
        },
        {
          "kind": "codeFill",
          "payload": {
            "prompt": "Keep only the positive numbers.",
            "codeBefore": "result = [n for n in nums ",
            "codeAfter": " n > 0]",
            "choices": ["if", "when", "where"],
            "correctIndex": 0,
            "explanation": "if filters the items before they go into the new list."
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "python-a3",
      "languageID": "python",
      "tier": "advanced",
      "order": 13,
      "title": "Reading from files",
      "summary": "Open a file and read its contents.",
      "xpReward": 70,
      "steps": [
        {
          "kind": "explainer",
          "payload": {
            "title": "with open(...) as f",
            "body": "The with block opens a file and automatically closes it when you're done — no leaks. Use f.read() to grab everything, or loop over f to read line by line.",
            "codeSample": "with open(\"notes.txt\") as f:\n    text = f.read()\nprint(text)"
          }
        },
        {
          "kind": "mcq",
          "payload": {
            "prompt": "Why use with open() instead of just open()?",
            "options": ["It's faster", "It closes the file automatically", "It makes the file bigger"],
            "correctIndex": 1,
            "explanation": "The with block cleans up — you can't forget to close the file."
          }
        },
        {
          "kind": "codeFill",
          "payload": {
            "prompt": "Open the file in read mode.",
            "codeBefore": "with open(\"data.txt\", ",
            "codeAfter": ") as f:",
            "choices": ["\"r\"", "\"w\"", "\"a\""],
            "correctIndex": 0,
            "explanation": "\"r\" is read mode; \"w\" is write; \"a\" is append."
          }
        }
      ]
